<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,726,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">
Hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[362,435,726,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[320,1258,744,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[320,1258,744,1890]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., adult male. (A) Head. (B) Thorax. (C) Wing. (D) Hypopygium, dorsal view. (E) Right gonostylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495313/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
D–E, 2A–C): Tergite IX with 10 scattered setae; lateroposterior margin lobular, rounded. Anal point broad and bilobed apically. Phallapodeme 60 µm long. Sternapodeme markedly arched and slender anteriorly. Superior volsella asymmetrically arched, 56 µm long. Gonocoxite robust, subcylindrical, 110 µm long, 77 µm wide; with a group of about 20 short robust bristles on the dorsomedian surface, mostly arising from raised tubercles; inner margin with a deep basal concavity, covered by bristles. Gonostylus as in 
<figureCitation box="[1179,1281,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[320,1258,744,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[320,1258,744,1890]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., adult male. (A) Head. (B) Thorax. (C) Wing. (D) Hypopygium, dorsal view. (E) Right gonostylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495313/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figures 1</figureCitation>
E and 2C, 70 µm long, 35µm maximum width (at the base); outer edge straight, forming a right angle to the base; apical lobe elongated and curved, 35 µm long, with a single setae rising from a distinct basal tubercle on external margin, megaseta lanceolate, 11 µm long, without dorsal lamella; subapical inner lobe 16 µm long, 5 µm wide at base, distally pointed, with a single seta ventrally; basal inner lobe 10 µm long, with 4 bristles arising from prominent tubercles. HR1.83. HV4.52.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,726,1978]" box="[199,1138,1086,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,1086,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Pupa (n=1).</emphasis>
Total length 
<quantity box="[487,590,1087,1111]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="370" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.10 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: cephalothorax and abdomen brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,726,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">
Cephalothorax (
<figureCitation box="[381,453,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1627,1649]" captionTargetBox="[314,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[313,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Thoracic horn. (B) Wing sheath. (C) Abdomen. (D) Tergite VII – VIII and Anal lobe." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495315/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figs 3</figureCitation>
A–B, 4A–B). Frontal apotome triangular. Wing sheath smooth, 773 µm long and 310 µm wide (
<figureCitation box="[266,326,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1627,1649]" captionTargetBox="[314,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[313,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Thoracic horn. (B) Wing sheath. (C) Abdomen. (D) Tergite VII – VIII and Anal lobe." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495315/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Fig 3</figureCitation>
B). Thoracic horn, subcylindrical, tapering basally, 238 µm long, maximum width 58 µm; external membrane hyaline, with scattered blunt spines; respiratory atrium thin-walled, almost filling entire thoracic horn volume and connected to the plastron plate by a narrow, elongated, discontinuous central duct; plastron plate small, hyaline, somewhat oval-shaped, with surface facing up, 17 µm long, 32 µm wide (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1141,1266,1291]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1627,1649]" captionTargetBox="[314,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[313,1285,213,1592]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Thoracic horn. (B) Wing sheath. (C) Abdomen. (D) Tergite VII – VIII and Anal lobe." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495315/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Figs 3</figureCitation>
A, 4A). Basal lobe absent; thoracic comb very weak, with 4 low rounded tubercles. Thoracic membrane rugose, with a dense covering of blunt, rounded tubercle; with a well-developed triangular-shaped prealar tubercle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,726,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">
Abdomen. Scar on TI absent. T I–VIII with large field of shagreen; anal lobe with shagreen on basal half. Segment II with 5 LS setae, LS1–3 arising from the segment base (
<figureCitation box="[878,940,1410,1435]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[328,1266,205,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[268,1319,193,1962]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Frontal apotome. (B) Thoracic horn. (C) LS setae of abdominal segment II. (D) LS setae of abdominal segment III. (E) Anal lobe and male genital sac, left in ventral view, right in dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495316/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Fig 4</figureCitation>
B); S III with 3 LS setae in the basal 1/3 and a group of about 7 fine filaments on the posterolateral corner (
<figureCitation box="[852,915,1449,1474]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[328,1266,205,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[268,1319,193,1962]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Frontal apotome. (B) Thoracic horn. (C) LS setae of abdominal segment II. (D) LS setae of abdominal segment III. (E) Anal lobe and male genital sac, left in ventral view, right in dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495316/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Fig 4</figureCitation>
C); S IV–VII with a lateral fringe of fine setae and a further group of multiserial setae on the posterolateral corner, VIII with 5 LS setae. Anal lobe rounded, 421 µm long, 640 µm wide at base, with distinct apical projection, pointed at apex, 95 µm long; outer border of anal lobe convex, with some scattered short spinules distal from the anal macrosetae, inner border straight (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1401,1557,1582]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[328,1266,205,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[268,1319,193,1962]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Djalmabatista patamona sp. nov., pupa. (A) Frontal apotome. (B) Thoracic horn. (C) LS setae of abdominal segment II. (D) LS setae of abdominal segment III. (E) Anal lobe and male genital sac, left in ventral view, right in dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/495316/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="370">Fig 4</figureCitation>
D). Male genital sac 302 µm long, 434 µm wide at base, wedge-shaped, apically truncate, almost reaching the base of apical projection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
